commitResults.messageTitle: Add find by free time and for multiple find filters
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, we only can find users by name or module.

Extending find functionality allows us to
find TAs by free time. We also want to allow for
multiple find filters, so users can execute more
specific search queries.

I have created a new AvailableTimePredicate class
which implements Predicate to check if a TA's free
time falls within a specific interval.

Creating another Predicate class allows for
abstraction to not be broken, especially in the
FindCommandParser class.

Predicate classes are currently in person package.

More Predicate classes have been created and it is
cluttering the person package.

Shifting the Predicate classes into the new
predicate package.

To prevent unnecessary clutter in the person
package.

FindCommand tests were failing due to changes to
the command.

Modified tests to accommodate new FindCommand
formats.

To ensure that we have sufficient test coverage
for the FindCommand.

Current FindCommand message usage does not reflect
new changes made to the command.

To let the user know how to use the new features
we added to the FindCommand.

Add more examples of how to use the command.

To let the users have a better idea of how to use
the command.

commitResults.messageTitle: Enable assertions in gradle build file
Fix invalid range in isInBetween function
commitResults.messageBody:
Invalid interval range is being used in current
implementation when comparing two intervals.

Fixing this would allow us to find TAs by
FreeTime more accurately.

For a current TimeInterval A, that is checking
against a TimeInterval B, we are checking,
* from of A is before or equal to from of B
* to of A is after or equal to to of B

To allow users to have a visual indication of what filters
have been applied to attain the search results.

We assume that TAs are only available from Monday to Friday

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor time in Lesson class into TimeInterval
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the start time and end time of lesson is handled directly by the Lesson class.

For better OOP, the time class is refactor into TimeInterval class.

There is a bug when refactoring time interval in lesson, causing the initial addressbook to be empty when launched.

This is fixed by implementing hashcode inside the TimeInterval class

Now, we restrict phone numbers to be between 3-10 digits to ensure that only valid phone numbers are keyed in.

Initially, Telegram handle input can accept any special characters.
